Here's the complete migration with key pitfalls explained:

## Migrated ASP.NET Core (.NET 8) Code

```csharp
using Microsoft.AspNetCore.Authorization;
using Microsoft.AspNetCore.Mvc;

public class ReportController : Controller
{
    // PITFALL 1: Web Forms event handlers (btnExport_Click) don't exist in MVC.
    // Replace with action methods that return IActionResult.

    [HttpPost]
    public IActionResult Export()
    {
        var data = GenerateReport();

        // PITFALL 2: Response.Clear(), Response.Write(), Response.End() are gone.
        // Response.End() threw ThreadAbortException internally — there is no
        // equivalent in ASP.NET Core because Kestrel doesn't abort threads.
        // Use FileContentResult or ContentResult instead.

        var bytes = System.Text.Encoding.UTF8.GetBytes(data);
        return File(bytes, "text/csv", "report.csv");
    }

    [HttpPost]
    public IActionResult ProcessAction()
    {
        // PITFALL 3: Response.Redirect("/login", true) called Thread.Abort()
        // to stop execution. ASP.NET Core redirects are just return values —
        // execution naturally stops when you return.

        if (!User.Identity?.IsAuthenticated ?? true)
        {
            return Redirect("/login");
            // No Thread.Abort, no endResponse parameter. Returning ends the action.
        }

        try
        {
            ProcessRequest();
            return Redirect("/success");
        }
        // PITFALL 4: Remove all ThreadAbortException catches.
        // They cannot occur in ASP.NET Core — Thread.Abort() is not supported
        // in .NET 6+ and throws PlatformNotSupportedException if called.
        catch (Exception ex)
        {
            LogError(ex);
            return Redirect("/error");
        }
    }
}
```

## Key Pitfalls Summary

| .NET Framework Pattern | Problem in .NET 8 | Fix |
|---|---|---|
| `Response.End()` | Doesn't exist; `Thread.Abort` is gone | Return `IActionResult` |
| `Response.Redirect(url, true)` | `endResponse` param relied on `Thread.Abort` | Return `Redirect()` |
| `catch (ThreadAbortException)` | Never thrown; masks real bugs if left in | Delete the catch block |
| `Response.Write(data)` | No synchronous write to response body | Return `File()` / `Content()` |
| `Response.AddHeader(...)` | Removed | Headers set via result types or `Response.Headers.Append()` |
| `User.Identity.IsAuthenticated` | `Identity` can be `null` | Null-check, or use `[Authorize]` |

## Bonus: Use `[Authorize]` Instead of Manual Checks

```csharp
// In Program.cs — configure auth middleware
builder.Services.AddAuthentication(/* ... */);
app.UseAuthentication();
app.UseAuthorization();

// Then simply:
[Authorize]
[HttpPost]
public IActionResult ProcessAction()
{
    // Unauthenticated users never reach here — framework redirects to login.
    ProcessRequest();
    return Redirect("/success");
}
```

**The core mental model shift**: In ASP.NET Framework, you *imperatively wrote* to the response stream and *aborted threads* to stop processing. In ASP.NET Core, action methods *return result objects* — the framework handles the HTTP response after your code exits cleanly. No thread aborts, no `Response.End()`, no swallowed exceptions.
